Search form

  • Mayor and Council Salary Increase May Appear on November Ballot

    The Citizens' Commission on Public Service and Compensation (CCPSC) recommends a Nov. 5, 2019 ballot measure to let voters decide on Mayor and Council salary increases. 

  • Take a Pledge to Save Water

    Join residents in Tucson and other cities across the nation in pledging to save water and other natural resources during the Wyland Foundation’s 2019 National Mayors' Challenge for Water Conservation, now through April 30.

  • Mexican-American History Museum Honors Women of Mariachi Music

    A new museum exhibit in Tucson highlights the history of women involved in mariachi music. The Trailblazing Women of Mariachi Music tells the stories of the early female pioneers of mariachi, including a special focus on Tucson women who influenced the genre.

  • City Seeking Input on "A" Mountain Access

    The City of Tucson has a survey to better understand how and when our community uses Sentinel Peak Park (also known as “A” Mountain).

  • Brush and Bulky Door Hangers No Longer Will Be Delivered

    Single-family residential customers inside the city limits no longer receive door hanger notifications for Brush and Bulky service from the City of Tucson's Environmental & General Services Department.

  • Interactive Map of Tucson Murals

    The artwork of local, national, and international muralists is on display in the City of Tucson. A new map from the City's GIS team shows the location of the murals and explains what they mean.

  • Tucson Delivers Better Streets and a Safer City

    Tucson Delivers is the program to fund better streets and a safer city through a five year, half-cent sales tax increase overwhelmingly approved by voters in May 2017.
